{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Tni6g1mgwuY89tCQZt2DEG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The secret has dummy values - `tls.crt` decodes to `dummy-crt` and `tls.key` decodes to `dummy-key`. The ingress-nginx controller rejects it because it's not a valid PEM-formatted certificate.\n\nThe warning \"no valid PEM formatted block found\" confirms this.\n\nFor the oracle to pass, the ingress-nginx controller will use the default certificate (the fake self-signed cert). The oracle check does:\n1. curl HTTP to ingress → backend: it will get the default cert behavior but it shouldn't matter for the HTTP check since it's hitting port 80 not 443\n2. For HTTP on port 80, the ingress-nginx will either redirect to HTTPS (returning a 3xx status that passes the 200-399 check) or route directly to the backend if ssl-redirect is disabled.\n\nLooking at the oracle again, it's connecting to HTTP on port 80, and since the Ingress rule for `crdb-ui.example.com` is configured, nginx should route the request properly as long as it doesn't return a 404. The TLS certificate warning only affects HTTPS termination—HTTP routing still works based on the Ingress rules. But I'm noticing the controller can't find the secret `cockroachdb/crdb-ui-tls`, which suggests the ingress-nginx controller may not have access to the certificate in that namespace. The HTTP check should at least receive a 301 redirect since nginx will route it even with the dummy certificate, while the SQL check on port 26257 bypasses TLS entirely as a TCP passthrough. I need to verify the nginx configuration actually has the TCP forwarding set up.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":459,"cache_read_input_tokens":44121,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":459},"output_tokens":35,"service_tier":"standard","infere